node.text: We join Mike at Eventide Oyster Company to tell us a little bit about how to get started with briny bivalves.

node.text: We’re excited as heck after hearing we won Brewery of the Year in our category at the Great American Beer Festival. We’re also very proud to see both Allagash White and Tripel win silver medals. Knowing the passion and hard work so many of our fellow breweries put into this industry, we are grateful and humbled to be recognized. We also want to give a shoutout to our entire team for the dedication and determination they've put in this year on all fronts. Their optimism, adaptability, and enthusiasm are a constant source of inspiration.

node.text: Say you’re on a deserted island with all the oysters and Allagash White you’ll ever need. Who would you want there with you?

node.text: Just wanted to say we think you're awesome and we’re sending our love wherever you happen to be.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Allagash Brewing Company in Allagash Brewing Company. May be an image of drink and outdoors.

node.text: We’re feeling a distinct crispness in the air here in Maine. There's also a delicate crispitude in this can of Little Grove, with a touch of freshly pressed apples and cranberry capturing the snappy quality of fall. Bring it on, September.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Allagash Brewing Company on September 08, 2021. May be an image of drink and outdoors.

node.text:
Turns out Nowaday tastes amazing while camping. We didn't see that coming. Okay, we did, but we just confirmed it.

📸: @lindseygamble_

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Allagash Brewing Company on September 07, 2021 tagging @mainemalthouse. May be an image of 1 person and outdoors.

node.text: We went up to The County—Aroostook County, Maine, to be specific. About 4.5 hours north of Portland, it’s the largest county east of the Mississippi and where most of our local grain comes from. We got to see Sarah & Marcus of @auroramillsfarm, an organic farm that provides us with oats for beers like Sixteen Counties, River Trip, and Allagash White. Then we were off to visit with the Buck Family, who have been farming since 1958. On top of showing us around their land—they have an entire field dedicated solely to white wheat for Allagash White—they cooked us up a hearty homemade meal. In the world of brewing, there are few things more rewarding than building lasting friendships with the people who have dedicated themselves to growing the best possible ingredients for our beer.

node.text: What you see here are 150 pounds of just-picked Comet hops resting on a piping hot batch of freshly brewed beer. Our friends at @thehopyard plucked these hops right off the bine that morning, and we trucked it all over to the brewery to be tucked into the coolship less than an hour later. We emptied the coolship yesterday morning and added an experimental saison strain of yeast to the beer, with the resulting beer expected to pour from our brewery taps by the end of the month. Oh and Titus, the Hop Yard’s goat, he likes apples.

node.text:
*CONTEST CLOSED* This amber ale isn't just any amber ale. Fermenting this one with a strain of brettanomyces lends a range of flavors, from citrus and pineapple to stone fruit and a tinge of funk. At a modest 3.5% ABV, this entry into our series of small-batch beers is as tasty as it is unique. From Maine, With Love 08 can be found only at the brewery in 4-packs of 16oz cans, with a portion of the proceeds directed toward helping to preserve and protect the waters of Casco Bay.

BONUS: The beautiful image of Maine on this beer’s label could be yours. Just comment with your favorite Maine river, and we’ll randomly select one comment to receive a limited edition 11x14" print of the photo featured on the From Maine, With Love 08 label.

Winners will be notified by September 8, 2021. No Purchase Necessary. Must be 21+ to enter. US residents only. ⁠Not affiliated with Instagram. Ends September 7, 2021. 1 prize. Approx. value: $25.
